    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nEmpty files (actual empty ones, without any eol chars) cannot be properly trusted at the moment, nvim asks for trust infinitely even if it's already `:trust`ed.\n\nPossibly related: #31241\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- `touch empty`\n- `:=vim.secure.read(\"empty\")`\n- choose to view file and `:trust` in the new window\n-  `:=vim.secure.read(\"empty\")` and see the trust prompt again\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIt should be possible to `:trust` empty files.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nnot applicable\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 6.18; Android 14\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWezTerm; Termux\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nnixpkgs; termux-packages",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "NOTE: `:trust` is new territory for me, so take my analysis with a grain of salt/if this comment is unwarranted. I'd like to learn about the right approach here.\n\nObv, the bug is a mismatch between the two trust paths: `vim.secure.read()` hashes file on disk but `:trust` / `vim.secure.trust({ bufnr = ... })` hashes a reconstruction of the buffer text joined by newlines. For a zero-byte file this matters (`'' != '\\n'`), causing the bug.\n\nI conceieve of two solutions:\n\n1. **Lua-side empty-file special case**. keep the current structure and special-case (smallest patch, fixes it locally for me). The tradeoff is that it still relies on this asymmetric reconstruction mechanism which is lossy and doesn't sit right with me from a design POV.\n2. **Core-side trust hashing**: move the buffer-side trust hash stuff into core, to entirely circumvent the aforementioned trade-off. Here, trusting an unchanged buffer would use the original raw file hash. Further, trusting a changed buffer would use the exact byte stream the buffer would write now. \n\nObviously (2) is a larger change but IMO the correct one. This is because empty files are not the only time in which this issue comes to light - I am certain there are other scenarios in which nvim-recreated buffer contents are not identical to on-disk contents (e.g. alternative file formats).",
