        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I checked the eol options and they don't fully explain this bug although they are part of the current mismatch. Namely, for a normal non-empty buffer, buffer-side `trust` hashing ignores 'fixeol' and I reproduced a case where that makes the `:trust` hash differ from what `:w` emits.\n\nBut for the actual empty-file reproduction, I locallly patched making the lua-side `'fixeol'`-aware and this (expectedly) still didn't fix it. Specifically the default empty-file case `:trust` still hashes `'\\n'` while the same `:w` of that (unchanged empty) buffer makes a 0-byte file.\n\nThis is because empty buffers take a [separate core write path](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/938c1e2194a7188d994e95d1f331717f1e445cb7/src/nvim/bufwrite.c#L1183-L1185)-this is _not_ just a matter of checking 'fixeol'/'eol'. \n\nTL;DR `'fixeol','eol'` are missing in the current reconstruction but regardless `:trust` hashes a simplified reconstruction instead of something that fully matches nvim's underlying C write/read behavior.\n\nNGL your comment convinces me a bit more toward reusing a single underlying impl/recipe rather than building out (seemingly) redundant logic but I leave this commentary to others.",
